<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>GIS on KevCaz's Website</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/tags/gis/</link><description>Recent content in GIS on KevCaz's Website</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><copyright>Content under CC0 1.0 Universal unless otherwise specified.</copyright><lastBuildDate>Tue, 20 Nov 2018 00:00:00 +0000</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://kevcaz.github.io/tags/gis/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Find the Coordinate Reference System (CRS) you need</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/11/2018-11-20_find_the_coordinate/</link><pubDate>Tue, 20 Nov 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/11/2018-11-20_find_the_coordinate/</guid><description>&lt;p>For the manipulation of spatial objects and spatial analyses, I mainly use R,
meaning that I use R packages that turn R into a powerful Geographic Information
System (GIS). Before 2017, I was using &lt;a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/sp">sp&lt;/a>,
&lt;a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rgdal">rgdal&lt;/a>, &lt;a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/rgeos">rgeos&lt;/a> for vector objects and &lt;a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/raster">raster&lt;/a>
for raster objects. Now I use a combination of &lt;a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/sf">sf&lt;/a>
(created to replace sp, rgoes and rgdal), raster and sf and &lt;a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/mapview">mapview&lt;/a>.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>One of the most common manipulation is to convert coordinates
(see &lt;code>sf::st_transform()&lt;/code> in &lt;code>raster::projectRaster()&lt;/code>). With my previous
set up one one of the main difficulty was to find the right &lt;a href="https://proj4.org/">proj4&lt;/a> string,
For instance, to use &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_Transverse_Mercator_coordinate_system">UTM&lt;/a> for the zone 17N, with &lt;strong>rgdal&lt;/strong> I used to write:&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Clip, but crop first!</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/11/2018-11-10_clip_but_crop/</link><pubDate>Sat, 10 Nov 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2018/11/2018-11-10_clip_but_crop/</guid><description>&lt;p>I often clip raster in R, with &lt;a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/sf/index.html">sf&lt;/a>
and &lt;a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/raster/index.html">raster&lt;/a> it
is straightforward and efficient. That said, I&amp;rsquo;d like to mention one tip
tip R users that clip should be aware of: cropping before clipping.
It does significantly improve the performance, as shown in the R script below:&lt;/p>
